.TH roe 1 "2026" "roe 1.0.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
roe \- a disassembler fit for humans
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B roe
.I file
.br
.B roe
.I file symbol
.RI [ options ]
.br
.B roe
.I file
.B \-\-section
.I name
.RI [ options ]
.br
.B roe
.I file
.RB { \-\-all | \-D }
.RI [ options ]
.br
.B roe
.B \-\-completions
.I shell
.br
.B roe
.RB { \-\-help | \-h }
.RI [ topic ]
.br
.B roe
.RB { \-\-version | \-V }
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B roe
is a command\-line disassembler that aims to make machine code readable by
people rather than only by other tools. It reads an object file, executable,
shared library, or static archive member, disassembles it with the Capstone
engine, and prints output that preserves addresses, resolves symbols and
relocations to their names, labels branch targets, and previews the
destinations of in\-function jumps and calls inline. Raw instruction bytes are
hidden by default and shown only on request.
.PP
With no symbol argument,
.B roe
lists the functions discovered in
.IR file .
Given a symbol, it disassembles that single function with cross\-function calls
resolved to symbol names, relocations annotated inline by name, and local
branches rewritten as readable labels. ELF input is fully supported;
Mach\-O, PE, and archive containers are recognized.
.PP
The tool was prompted by Linus Torvalds in the Linux kernel mailing list
thread
.RB \(lq "odd objtool \(aqunreachable instruction\(aq warning" \(rq
(29 October 2025), where he observed that
.BR objdump (1)
flags are hard to remember, that its output trades readability against
information, that relocations are printed as raw addresses instead of symbol
names, and that there is no way to preview the target of a jump or call. His
summary was that the output is
.RB \(lq "not fit for humans" \(rq .
The name
.B roe
and this manual are a direct response to that complaint.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-\-all ", " \-D
Disassemble every executable section instead of listing functions.
.TP
.BI \-\-arch " name"
Override the detected architecture. Useful for code the container cannot
disambiguate, for example
.B thumb
or
.BR riscv64 .
.TP
.BI \-\-calls " symbol"
List only the functions that call or branch to
.IR symbol .
.TP
.BI \-\-completions " shell"
Emit a shell completion script to standard output and exit. The argument is
one of
.BR bash ", " zsh ", " fish ", or " powershell .
.TP
.BI \-\-contains " string"
List only the functions whose body references the given
.IR string .
.TP
.BI \-\-grep " regex"
List only the functions whose name matches the given regular expression.
.TP
.B \-\-help ", " \-h " [\fItopic\fP]"
Show help and exit. An optional
.I topic
selects a focused page; topics are
.BR usage ", " formats ", " arches ", " examples ", " config ", and " json .
.TP
.B \-\-json
Emit machine\-readable JSON instead of formatted text. Combine with
.B \-\-no\-color
when piping to other programs.
.TP
.B \-\-no\-color
Disable ANSI color in the output, as for pipes and log files. Color is also
disabled when the
.B NO_COLOR
environment variable is set.
.TP
.B \-\-no\-pager
Do not page long output through the pager. Paging is also disabled when the
.B NO_PAGER
environment variable is set or when output is not a terminal.
.TP
.BI \-\-section " name"
Disassemble the named section, for example
.IR .text ", instead of listing functions."
.TP
.B \-\-show\-bytes
Show the raw instruction bytes alongside each instruction. Bytes are hidden
by default.
.TP
.B \-\-source
Interleave source lines drawn from debug information with the disassembly.
.TP
.B \-\-stats
Print per\-function statistics: size, basic block count, branch count, and
nesting depth.
.TP
.B \-\-version ", " \-V
Show the version together with build information, supported architectures,
and recognized formats, then exit.
.TP
.B \-\-watch
Re\-run automatically whenever the input file changes on disk.
.TP
.BI \-\-xref " symbol"
Show every call site of
.IR symbol .
.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
List the functions in a binary:
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
roe vmlinux.o
.EE
.RE
.PP
Disassemble a single function with resolved symbols, labeled branches, and
inline previews:
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
roe vmlinux.o handle_mm_fault
.EE
.RE
.PP
Disassemble a named section:
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
roe a.out \-\-section .text
.EE
.RE
.PP
Disassemble every executable section:
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
roe a.out \-\-all
.EE
.RE
.PP
Emit JSON and post\-process it with
.BR jq (1):
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
roe a.out main \-\-json \-\-no\-color | jq .
.EE
.RE
.PP
Find C++ methods by matching the function names against a regular expression:
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
roe libfoo.so \-\-grep \(aq::\(aq
.EE
.RE
.PP
Show every call site of a symbol:
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
roe a.out \-\-xref malloc
.EE
.RE
.PP
Report per\-function statistics:
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
roe a.out \-\-stats
.EE
.RE
.PP
Show raw instruction bytes for one function:
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
roe a.out main \-\-show\-bytes
.EE
.RE
.PP
Interleave source lines from debug information:
.PP
.RS 4
.EX
roe a.out main \-\-source
.EE
.RE
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
Usage error, such as an unknown flag or a missing argument.
.TP
.B 2
File or format error, such as a missing file or an unrecognized container.
.TP
.B 3
Disassembly error, such as a failure in the disassembler or symbol resolver.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B NO_COLOR
When set to any value, disable ANSI color, as with
.BR \-\-no\-color .
.TP
.B NO_PAGER
When set to any value, disable the pager, as with
.BR \-\-no\-pager .
.TP
.B PAGER
The pager command used for long output. Defaults to
.BR "less \-R" .
.TP
.B XDG_CONFIG_HOME
Base directory for configuration. The configuration file is read from
.IR $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/roe/config.toml ,
defaulting to
.I ~/.config/roe/config.toml
when unset.
.TP
.B ROE_CONFIG
Explicit path to the configuration file, overriding the search based on
.BR XDG_CONFIG_HOME .
.SH FILES
.TP
.I $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/roe/config.toml
Per\-user configuration file on Linux. When
.B XDG_CONFIG_HOME
is unset the path is
.IR ~/.config/roe/config.toml .
On macOS the file is
.I ~/Library/Application Support/roe/config.toml
and on Windows it is
.IR %APPDATA%\eroe\econfig.toml .
The location can be overridden with the
.B ROE_CONFIG
environment variable.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR objdump (1),
.BR readelf (1),
.BR nm (1),
.BR addr2line (1)
